evels in patients receiving chemotherapy." Am J Med 87 (1989): 505-10[7] Jarosinski PF, Moscow JA, Alexander MS, et al "Altered phenytoin clearance during intensive chemotherapy for acute lymphoblastic leukemia." J Pediatr 112 (1988): 996-9[8] "Product Information. Oncovin (vincristine)." Lilly, Eli and Company, Indianapolis, IN.[9] Cerner Multum, Inc. "Australian Product Information." O 0[10] Cerner Multum, Inc. "UK Summary of Product Characteristics." O 0[11] Fleisher D, Sheth N, Kou JH "Phenytoin interaction with enteral feedings administered through nasogastric tubes." JPEN J Parenter Enteral Nutr 14 (1990): 513-6[12] Krueger KA, Garnett WR, Comstock TJ, Fitzsimmons WE, Karnes HT, Pellock JM "Effect of two administration schedules of an enteral nutrient formula on phenytoin bioavailability." Epilepsia 28 (1987): 706-12[13] Haley CJ, Nelson J "Phenytoin-enteral feeding interaction." DICP 23 (1989): 796-8[14] Faraji B, Yu PP "Serum phenytoin levels of patients on gastrostomy tube feeding." J Neurosci Nurs 30 (1998): 55-9[15] Au Yeung SC, Ensom MH "Phenytoin and enteral feedings: does evidence support an interaction?" Ann Pharmacother 34 (2000): 896-905[16] Sandor P, Sellers EM, Dumbrell M, Khouw V "Effect of short- and long-term alcohol use on phenytoin kinetics in chronic alcoholics." Clin Pharmacol Ther 30 (1981): 390-7[17] Ozuna J, Friel P "Effect of enteral tube feeding on serum phenytoin levels." J Neurosurg Nurs 16 (1984): 289-91[18] Guidry JR, Eastwood TF, Curry SC "Phenytoin absorption in volunteers receiving selected enteral feedings." West J Med 150 (1989): 659-61[19] Marvel ME, Bertino JS "Comparative effects of an elemental and a complex enteral feeding formulation on the absorption of phenytoin suspension." JPEN J Parenter Enteral Nutr 15 (1991): 316-8[20] "Product Information. Dilantin (phenytoin)." Parke-Davis, Morris Plains, NJ.[21] Doak KK, Haas CE, Dunnigan KJ, et al. "Bioavailability of phenytoin acid and phenytoin sodium with enteral feedings."